Kickstarter is getting a lot of ink for having "converted" from for-profit to Public Benefit status, meaning that its business decisions will occasionally take into account something other than profit, and that it will donate 5% of after-tax profits to worthy causes.  <a title="Target Corporate Contributions Program" href="https://corporate.target.com/corporate-responsibility/" target="_blank">But Target Corporation, as purely for-profit as one could imagine, does exactly the same thing</a>.  As Huttler says,
<blockquote>The distinction between non-profit and for-profit work may be increasingly blurry, but it’s not meaningless. Becoming a Benefit Corporation doesn’t change a company’s DNA. In the case of Kickstarter, that DNA is about raising capital for commercial ventures. The notion that Benefit Corporations are some kind of upgraded version of non-profits is factually confused and undermines the work of actual non-profit organizations.</blockquote>
Public Benefit Corporations are a public relations device, designed to make ordinary corporate citizenship into something praiseworthy.  And the corporations which insist they're unable to consider the public interest without risking a shareholder revolt---saying that the ONLY duty of a corporation is to maximize profit for owners---are simply lying. Or quoting Milton Friedman, which amounts to the same thing.

Until the 1980s, few American corporations would have been able to show their faces unless they had a pet charity or two.  Only the most extreme version of capitalism could even countenance the idea that <em>share</em>holders are the only <em>stake</em>holders in institutions which use public resources.  And every corporation does, whether in the form of out-and-out subsidies or merely (merely!) our systems of transportation and law enforcement which make it possible to manufacture and distribute products without paying bribes or having your patent stolen.

Again, a salute to Adam Huttler and <a title="Fractured Atlas website" href="https://www.fracturedatlas.org/" target="_blank">Fractured Atlas</a> for knowing the difference between gold and <a title="Fool's Gold" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyrite" target="_blank">pyrite</a>.

